  "prompt": "Which IB subjects should I choose for economics?",
  "response": "When selecting International Baccalaureate (IB) subjects for a focus on economics, it's important to consider the prerequisites of the university programs you're interested in, as well as subjects that will provide you with a strong foundation in economics. Generally, the following subjects are recommended:\n\n1. **Economics (Group 3: Individuals and Societies)**: It\u2019s essential to choose Economics as this directly pertains to your area of interest and will provide you with a solid understanding of economic theories, principles, and real-world applications.\n\n2. **Mathematics (Group 5)**: Depending on your comfort level and future studies, consider:\n   - **Mathematics: Analysis and Approaches (AA)** at Higher Level (HL): This is recommended if you are strong in mathematics and interested in a rigorous approach. Many economics programs, especially those at competitive universities, value strong math skills.\n   - **Mathematics: Applications and Interpretation (AI)** at Standard Level (SL): If you prefer a more practical and applied approach to mathematics, this could be suitable, though AA is generally preferred for economics.\n\n3. **Business Management or History (Group 3: Individuals and Societies)**: \n   - **Business Management**: Offers insight into corporate finance, business strategy, and operations, which can complement your economics studies.\n   - **History**: Understanding historical contexts and developments can enrich your analysis of economic trends and policies.\n\n4. **English or another Language (Group 1 or Group 2)**: Strong communication skills are crucial in economics, so taking a Language A or B course at a higher level can be beneficial.\n\n5. **Sciences (Group 4)**: While not directly related to economics, taking a science can develop your analytical and research skills. Some students select Environmental Systems and Societies due to its interdisciplinary nature, touching on economic issues related to sustainability.\n\nUltimately, the ideal combination depends on your academic strengths, interests, and the specific requirements of the universities you wish to apply to. Be sure to balance your selections with a mix of subjects that challenge you and play to your strengths.",
